<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRITISH VIEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am an Englishman who has spent the past two weeks on vacation with relatives 
in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
I am writing to comment on the subject of proportional representation, as 
raised by Matthew Shugart (letter, Jan. 1). He claims that Britain's electoral 
system "works," although the majority party almost never has a majority of 
votes. It does not work. 
</P>
<P>
We desperately need proportional representation and the coalitions that are 
likely to result from it. Only these can rescue us from the extremes of 
pendulum politics in which each government tends to undo the work of its 
predecessor. (This tendency is much more marked than in America, with its 
checks and balances). It has also intensified the divisions between the 
prosperous south and the economically disadvantaged north of England, Scotland 
and Wales. 
</P>
<P>
This apart, what kind of democracy can we really claim to be when, in the 1987 
election, 43% of the votes cast for Conservatives gained 60% of the seats in 
Parliament, but over 20% who voted for the center alliance gained 3% of the 
seats? 
</P>
<P>
TONY NOAKES 
</P>
<P>
Middlesex, England 
</P>
</TEXT>
