<HEADLINE>
<P>
A YIDDISH TERM EVOLVES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In "The American Jewish Experience" (Dec. 22), Elaine Woo referred to a common 
but mistaken explanation of the Yiddish term bobe mayse. 
</P>
<P>
 First, a bobe mayse is not merely an anecdote about the past but rather an old 
wives' tale, often of doubtful veracity. Moreover, while most Yiddish speakers 
believe that the expression derives from the Yiddish bobe (grandmother), it 
actually has a more literary antecedent: an early 16th-Century Yiddish romance 
called the "Bove-bukh" ("Bove-Book"), written in Italy. Its author, Elye 
Levita, borrowed from an earlier Italian source, which was in turn based on the 
escapades -- in English -- of one Bevis of Hampton. Via the Italian, Bevis 
became Bove. 
</P>
<P>
Once the Bove-bukh was no longer regular reading among Yiddish speakers, the 
term bove-mayse (Bove story) acquired its present folk etymology. 
</P>
<P>
JANET HADDA 
</P>
<P>
Associate Professor of Yiddish 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
