<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Hard Rock Cafe in New Orleans is caught between a rock and a hard city 
commission that has turned down a request for a "walk of fame" on the sidewalks 
surrounding the French Quarter eatery. The restaurant wants to install a dozen 
brass plaques, emblazoned with stars, as tributes to musicians who have visited 
the Hard Rock. Similar plaques have been planted at Hard Rock Cafes in other 
cities. The Vieux Carre Commission, which guards the architectural integrity of 
the French Quarter, the oldest section of the Mississippi River port city, said 
that the quarter should not be home to memorials for the living and that 
sidewalks should not be used for advertising. The cafe will resubmit the 
proposal. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
