2374 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
Q&amp;A: JOEL SLUTZKY; 
</P>
<P>
ANOTHER FUN FIRM IN ANAHEIM; 
</P>
<P>
ODETICS 'ASSOCIATES' WHO PLAY TOGETHER STAY TOGETHER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID OLMOS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the 1984 book "The 100 Best Companies to Work For in America," two Orange 
County businesses on opposite sides of Harbor Boulevard in Anaheim were among 
the elite. 
</P>
<P>
One was Disneyland. The other was Odetics. 
</P>
<P>
Disneyland, of course, needs no introduction. 
</P>
<P>
But most people haven't heard of Odetics Inc., a small high-technology company 
founded in 1969. Nor could they probably name its co-founder and chairman, Joel 
Slutzky. 
</P>
<P>
Even among high-tech companies, which have a reputation for stressing 
"quality-of-life" factors, Odetics is a bit of an oddball. 
</P>
<P>
Odetics has a Fun Committee that meets occasionally to plan ways for employees 
to, well, have fun. 
</P>
<P>
To celebrate the Los Angeles Lakers' National Basketball Assn. title last year, 
the Fun Committee planned "Lakers Day," during which anyone who came to work 
dressed in the team's colors was entitled to a free lunch in the company 
cafeteria. In years past, the committee also devised "Project Girth," where for 
every pound lost by an employee, the company donated $1 to his or her favorite 
charity. 
</P>
<P>
Odetics also has its own repertory theater company, which stages performances 
every few years. The last performance was "You Can't Take It With You" in the 
spring of 1987. 
</P>
<P>
The company's lobby is furnished with, among other things, footstools in the 
shape of human feet. In 1982, the company opened its Odexercise Center, which 
has an indoor heated pool and an exercise room that most health spas would be 
proud of. The facility offers aerobic dance classes and a health training 
program, and has a full-time fitness coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
There is more to Odetics than just fun, however. 
</P>
<P>
The company manufactures sophisticated space recorders that are carried on 
board the space shuttle and satellites, time-lapse videocassette recorders that 
are used in banks and convenience stores, and computerized cart machines used 
by television stations to automate their programming. Odetics also built a 
six-legged robot named Odex, which is now exhibited at the Smithsonian 
Institution in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
Odetics earned $896,938 on revenue of $49.7 million for its fiscal year ended 
March 31, 1988. For the 6 months ended Sept. 30, the firm earned $633,000 on 
revenue of $25.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
Slutzky, 49, was one of six Odetics co-founders. He earned undergraduate 
degrees in mechanical and electrical engineering from the University of 
Illinois, Champaign-Urbana, where he also was awarded a master's degree in 
mechanical engineering. He lives in Newport Beach with his wife Judy and their 
three children. 
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Times staff writer David Olmos, Slutzky discussed 
his company, his management philosophy and other issues. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Q. One of your company slogans is: "Odetics: not just another company." What 
does that slogan mean to you? 
</P>
<P>
A. I think it reflects a philosophy that is geared to a balance between the 
present and the future. We don't take the traditional price-earnings, the 'What 
did you do this quarter?' approach. We try to balance our short-term 
performance with where we see the long term. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Odetics is in the business of developing intelligent machines. What is an 
intelligent machine? 
</P>
<P>
A. Intelligent machines are machines that adapt to their environment. It's 
really a very broad term for the field of robotics. The original term robotics 
was picked up by manufacturing industry and was used for stationary robots used 
for welding or painting. In order to differentiate traditional robots from the 
factory robots, the industry coined the expression intelligent machines. 
Intelligent machines can run the gamut from artificial intelligence capability 
to machines that have sophisticated electronics and can do tasks that simpler 
machines can't do. 
</P>
<P>
Q. What kinds of intelligent machines do you see your company making in the 
future? 
</P>
<P>
A. We've defined four market areas: space, defense, nuclear and commercial 
applications. In the area of space we're very much interested in docking and 
berthing of satellites. Also service and maintenance of satellites. There are a 
number of applications for robots in the U.S. space station. We expect that 
there will be a number of platforms in space -- with electronic packages, power 
supplies and other equipment that will have to be replaced from time to time. 
The ability to have a servicing vehicle that can dock with the platform and 
change a bad component for a new one is important. I also think there are other 
areas, such as refueling in space or space construction, that will be a natural 
for robotics. In the area of defense, we've been concentrating on 
logistics-handling equipment (for example, a device attached to the end of a 
truck that could be used to pick up pallets of food or other military 
supplies). The third area is the nuclear industry. Our interest there is 
service and maintenance in nuclear power plants. We're currently building a 
robot for public utilities that would be used for doing routine maintenance in 
a nuclear plant, such as changing filters and turning valves. In the commercial 
area, which probably is the most fertile, we manufacture cart machines for the 
television industry. 
</P>
<P>
Q. If I could ask you to do some star-gazing, what kinds of intelligent 
machines are we going to be seeing 10 to 15 years from now? 
</P>
<P>
A. I think the trend is very clear. We're getting more sophisticated and 
smaller computers. These computers are allowing us to do more processing, 
quicker processing with more memory capability. We're also developing better 
sensors, which allows us to do many more things. In the area of defense, for 
instance, many of the philosophies and the equipment are geared for a historic 
perception of (combat). When you start looking at intelligent machines, you 
talk about eliminating people (from the task). And when you start talking about 
eliminating people, you start to rethink what that equipment should look like 
in a military scenario. 
</P>
<P>
Q. What are some examples of that? 
</P>
<P>
A. A tank, for instance, looks like a tank because it's been designed to 
protect people. If you were to design a peopleless tank, an autonomous tank, it 
would look completely different. It wouldn't need the armor to protect the 
people. It would be very lightweight and very fast. It would be a very 
revolutionary-type thing. (Intelligent machines) are going to affect military 
philosophies and strategies. In commercial use, there are many tasks that are 
just impossible for human beings to do or for which they need tools that don't 
exist today. Intelligent machines will allow us to do that. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Odetics has a reputation as a unique place to work. You have been quoted as 
saying that you try to create an environment of enjoyment for your employees. 
How did this get started? 
</P>
<P>
A. Well, first of all we don't call them employees. We call them associates. I 
think everyone is a reflection of their experiences. When we started the 
company on Day 1, we talked about trying to establish a company where there 
were no "we's" and "they's," where it was more of an "us." We wanted to create 
a family-type atmosphere in which the associates would be the company. And we 
have found that to be very successful. We quickly realized that we weren't 
getting the type of turnover that other companies were getting, that there were 
real dividends in that philosophy, that we didn't have the recruiting and the 
training costs. So, if anything, it was selfish motivation that kept that 
philosophy alive. It just makes good sense, not only for Odetics but for any 
company to do that. Because you can't replace experienced people. And there's 
no substitute for people who really care about what they're doing. If they feel 
like they're a part of it then they financially end up caring about it. 
</P>
<P>
Q. What is your turnover rate? 
</P>
<P>
A. In our space division, for instance, the average tenure of our associates is 
8 1/2 years. The turnover rate has been about 5% a year, which is extremely 
low. 
</P>
<P>
Q. But the swimming pool and the recreation facility cost money. Is there a 
payback? 
</P>
<P>
A. Absolutely. The cost of the facilities is really very small compared to the 
benefits. One benefit which is hard to put a dollar figure on is the 
communications and feedback that goes on in that kind of environment. You know, 
it's one thing to talk to somebody when you're wearing a suit and tie and 
they're wearing an assembly smock. You've already got a caste difference going 
in the discussion, which is going to bias some of the communication. It's 
another thing when you're both in your sweats and you're talking about what's 
going on in the company. It's a great reducer of barriers. So that's a benefit 
that you can't put a dollar figure on. There are other benefits which are more 
tangible -- the health and well-being and happiness of the people that are 
using those facilities. There are some real intangibles. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Of the tangibles, for example, do you find that people are not out sick as 
much? Have you studied the relationship there? 
</P>
<P>
A. We looked at it. And I think people are out sick less, but we might have 
more sprained ankles than other places. But it's more than the gym and the 
swimming pool. We have a number of tournaments. We have a Ping-Pong tournament, 
volleyball tournament, basketball tournament and corporate fitness cups. One 
has to appreciate how much time you spend in a company relative to the amount 
of time that you spend at home. If you take away the sleeping portion of the 
day, you actually spend more time at work than you do at home. So I've always 
felt that work should be interesting, challenging. You should want to get up in 
the morning. There's nothing worse than a static environment and a static set 
of conditions in working. 
</P>
<P>
Q. In a newspaper article a few years ago, your personnel manager at the time 
said that you are "as crazy as anybody gets." What did you think of that? 
</P>
<P>
A. My feeling about an article like that is that it's nice but that's not what 
we're all about. As far as my being crazy, when I looked at the article, I 
said, "I'm not crazy. If anything, I've lost too much of the child in me." But 
the more I thought about it, the less I took offense at it. I think that we all 
could use a little more child in us. Sometimes we get too serious and too hung 
up on what we're doing. The fact that every once in awhile you'll see something 
a little bit different here -- like at Easter you might see somebody running 
around in a bunny suit -- I think that's good. And if crazy means fostering 
that sort of thing or condoning it, then that's fine with me. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Although Odetics has been profitable for 18 consecutive years, your profit 
margins have not been as high as some other companies in your business. Is the 
company too busy having fun? 
</P>
<P>
A. The truth is that the amount of time you spend relaxing is very small and is 
necessary. When you have people that work hard and come in on Saturdays and 
sometimes on Sundays, they do that for a love of the company. When we make 
marginal profitability, it's because we've been putting our profits back into 
research and development. That has no reflection on the gym or the swimming 
pool. But people can draw their conclusion, and that's always a danger. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Has the image of Odetics as a fun place to work had any effect on how the 
company is perceived on Wall Street? 
</P>
<P>
A. No. I think we're really not a Wall Street company because we've taken a 
long-term view, and Wall Street is very much quarterly conscious. We have opted 
to do some things that, in the short term, don't help. For instance, we 
purchased these facilities (Odetics' headquarters building in Anaheim, which 
the company bought in 1984). If you were trying to placate Wall Street, you 
wouldn't do that because you don't really want the depreciation on your books. 
Depreciation hurts earnings, which hurts the price of the stock. 
</P>
<P>
Q. It's been said that one of the advantages Japanese corporations have over 
their American counterparts is that they're more willing to take a long-term 
approach to their markets, exchanging short-term profits for market share. 
Would you agree with that? 
</P>
<P>
A. I think that kind of spirit is something we see still in the Japanese 
market. I think the Japanese believe in market share and will do anything to 
establish market share. When you match that kind of a philosophy against a 
society that believes in earnings, then you have an imbalance. When the 
competition gets tough, the person who succeeds is the one who believes in 
market share, has a long-term outlook and is willing to wait out the situation. 
A person who believes in earnings is likely to throw in the towel and give up 
on an industry because it's not "earning enough." We've seen major American 
companies get out of a market because they didn't feel there was enough 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
Q. So you think the Japanese have the right strategy? 
</P>
<P>
A. The Japanese have been very patient. They've come into industries and tried 
to understand what is required to make them a success. And then they're willing 
to invest the time and effort to do that. You have to admire that. There's an 
awful lot of Japan-bashing going around. But anybody who is close to the 
situation has to admire their tenacity, their persistence and their desire to 
learn and succeed. We've got to do the same thing. We certainly don't want to 
become the Great Britain of the 21st Century. 
</P>
<P>
Q. What kind of future growth do you see for Odetics? 
</P>
<P>
A. We would like to see it become a $100-million company within the next 4 to 5 
years. We're taking it one objective at a time. I think we have a number of 
opportunities for good growth. What we really want is . . . to let the company 
grow in a logical, harmonious way. If you go too fast, it provides 
dislocations. If you go too slow, you've got financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
Q. What would you consider logical growth? 
</P>
<P>
A. At a growth rate of 20% to 30% a year, there is still a comfort factor. If 
the growth gets larger than that, you've got people coming through the front 
door so quickly that there is no way you can impart philosophies -- to tell 
them what we're all about or we're trying to achieve. The secret of a 
successful company is getting everyone steering in the same direction. You do 
that not by dictate, but through dialogue and by discussing where you're going. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Joel Slutzky is chairman and a co-fouder of Odetics, rated in 1984 book 
as one of nation's 100 best places to work. GARY AMBROSE / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
